Description: Calakmul Biosphere Reserve in Campeche, Mexico provided jungle backdrops for establishing shots of the Rebel base on Yavin IV in *Star Wars: A New Hope*.
Cardington Airship Sheds in Bedfordshire were used to film interior hangar scenes for the Rebel base on Yavin IV in *A New Hope* and later reused for other Star Wars films.
Death Valley National Park in California doubled as part of the desert planet Tatooine for *A New Hope*, with filming at sites like Dante's View, Desolation Canyon and Mesquite Flat Dunes.
The town of Ajim on the island of Djerba, Tunisia served as the exterior of Mos Eisley's cantina and other streets of Tatooine in *A New Hope*.
Elstree Film Studios near Borehamwood hosted interior sets for *A New Hope*, *The Empire Strikes Back*, and *Return of the Jedi* and later prequel/sequel films.
The linear dunes near Nefta, Tunisia (known as La Grande Dune) were used for the lifepod crash site and krayt-dragon skeleton shots on Tatooine in *A New Hope*.
Tikal's ancient Mayan temples provided exterior establishing shots of the Rebel base on Yavin IV at the end of *A New Hope*.
Shepperton Studios near London housed additional interior sets for the original trilogy and prequel films.

Placename: Imperial Sand Dunes (Buttercup Valley), California, USA
Description: The Imperial Sand Dunes near Yuma, Arizona-specifically Buttercup Valley-provided the location for the Great Pit of Carkoon and Jabba's sail-barge scenes in *Return of the Jedi*.

Hotel Sidi Idriss in Matmata is a troglodyte hotel that served as the interior of the Lars homestead on Tatooine in *A New Hope* and was revisited for Shmi Skywalker's funeral scene in *Attack of the Clones*.
The fortified granary Ksar Medenine in Médenine, Tunisia appeared as the slave quarters and Anakin Skywalker's childhood home in *The Phantom Menace*.
Ksar Ouled Soltane near Tataouine served as additional slave-quarters buildings for the Mos Espa scenes in *The Phantom Menace*.

Placename: Chott el Djerid (Lars Homestead Exterior), Tunisia
Description: The salt flats of Chott el Djerid hosted the exterior of the Lars homestead in *A New Hope*, *Attack of the Clones* and *Revenge of the Sith*; an igloo facade was built on the site.
A purpose-built set in the Eriguet dunes near Tozeur formed the Mos Espa marketplace and slave-quarter streets for *The Phantom Menace* and was reused in *Attack of the Clones*.
The rock formation Oung Jmel (Camel Head) near Tozeur was used as the landing site for Darth Maul's Sith Infiltrator and other desert shots in *The Phantom Menace*.
The gorge of Sidi Bouhlel-nicknamed Star Wars Canyon-was used for the Jundland Wastes where Tusken Raiders attack Luke in *A New Hope* and for podrace sniper shots in *The Phantom Menace*.
The Amghar Mosque on Djerba served as the exterior of Obi-Wan Kenobi's hut overlooking the Dune Sea in *A New Hope*.

Placename: Sidi Jemour Mosque (Tosche Station), Djerba, Tunisia
Description: The Sidi Jemour Mosque near Djerba appeared as Tosche Station (seen in deleted scenes) in *A New Hope*.
CTV Productions in Tunisia provided production facilities for *The Phantom Menace*.
Elstree Film Studios were again used for interior sets in *The Phantom Menace*.
Ksar Hadada's covered alleys were used as the Mos Espa slave-quarter backyards in *The Phantom Menace*.
The 18th-century Royal Palace of Caserta stood in for the Naboo Royal Palace interior in *The Phantom Menace*.
Leavesden Studios near Watford housed extensive sets and visual-effects stages for *The Phantom Menace* and other films.
Whippendell Woods near Watford provided the forest backdrop for Gungan scenes on Naboo in *The Phantom Menace*.
Villa del Balbianello on Lake Como was used as the lakeside retreat where Anakin and Padmé hide on Naboo in *Attack of the Clones*.
The Plaza de España in Seville served as the Naboo palace courtyard through which Anakin and Padmé walk in *Attack of the Clones*.
The snowy peaks of the Tre Cime di Lavaredo in the Italian Dolomites portrayed the planet Vandor in *Solo: A Star Wars Story* and provided the backdrop for the conveyex heist.
The decommissioned Fawley Power Station on Southampton Water doubled as the industrial planet Corellia in *Solo: A Star Wars Story*.
The island of Fuerteventura in the Canary Islands provided desert landscapes for the planet Savareen in *Solo: A Star Wars Story*.
Chott el Djerid's salt flats were revisited for the Lars homestead exterior and other Tatooine scenes in *Revenge of the Sith*.
Disney Studios Australia in Sydney hosted interior sets and bluescreen stages for *Revenge of the Sith*.
Footage of the alpine scenery around Grindelwald was composited into the planet Alderaan in *Revenge of the Sith*.
Shots of Guilin's karst mountains were used for Kashyyyk's backdrop in *Revenge of the Sith*.
Footage of eruptions on Mount Etna inspired the fiery landscape of Mustafar in *Revenge of the Sith*.
Phuket's tropical scenery was combined with digital elements for the planet Kashyyyk in *Revenge of the Sith*.
Shepperton Studios once again hosted interior sets for *Revenge of the Sith*.
The Hardangerjøkulen glacier near Finse provided the icy landscape of Hoth for *The Empire Strikes Back*.

Placename: Cheatham Grove (Grizzly Creek Redwoods State Park), California, USA
Description: Cheatham Grove in Grizzly Creek Redwoods State Park was used as the forest moon Endor in *Return of the Jedi* for the speeder-bike chase and Ewok village scenes.

Placename: Abu Dhabi Desert, United Arab Emirates
Description: Desert near Abu Dhabi stood in for the planet Jakku in *The Force Awakens*.

Placename: Bad Robot Productions, Santa Monica, USA
Description: Bad Robot's headquarters in Santa Monica served as production offices for *The Force Awakens*.
The scenic Derwentwater in England's Lake District was used for aerial plates during the attack on Starkiller Base in *The Force Awakens*.
Iceland's Krafla volcanic region provided otherworldly landscapes for Starkiller Base and was later reused in *Rogue One*.
Pinewood Studios has hosted many Star Wars films, including *The Force Awakens*, *The Last Jedi* and *The Rise of Skywalker*, providing sound stages such as the 007 Stage.
Puzzlewood's moss-covered gulleys and twisted trees represented Takodana's forest where Rey first faced Kylo Ren in *The Force Awakens*.
The disused RAF Greenham Common airfield served as the Resistance base on D'Qar in *The Force Awakens*.
The monastic island of Skellig Michael off Ireland's west coast appears as Luke Skywalker's refuge on Ahch-To in *The Force Awakens* and *The Last Jedi*.
Pinewood's 007 Stage housed large interior sets for *The Last Jedi*, including the interiors of Supreme Leader Snoke's ship and the Crait base.
Brow Head on the Mizen Peninsula provided dramatic coastal cliffs for Ahch-To scenes in *The Last Jedi*.
Ceann Sibéal (Sybil Head) on the Dingle Peninsula hosted the set of the ancient Jedi temple on Ahch-To in *The Last Jedi*.
Locations around the Dingle Peninsula were used for additional Ahch-To coastline shots in *The Last Jedi*.
The old town of Dubrovnik doubled as the luxury casino city of Canto Bight in *The Last Jedi*.
Malin Head in County Donegal served as another Ahch-To location, providing rugged cliffside scenery in *The Last Jedi*.
Bolivia's Salar de Uyuni, the world's largest salt flat, represented the mineral planet Crait during the climactic battle in *The Last Jedi*.
Cardington Studios' vast airship hangars were used to construct large sets for *The Rise of Skywalker* and *Rogue One*.
The sandstone desert of Wadi Rum served as the planet Pasaana in *The Rise of Skywalker* and doubled as the moon Jedha in *Rogue One*.
Baresdhoo is an uninhabited island in Laamu Atoll that formed part of the tropical battle scenes on Scarif in *Rogue One*.
Gan Island in Laamu Atoll provided additional beaches for Scarif's rebel assault in *Rogue One*.
Black Hangar Studios at Lasham Airfield housed interior sets for *Rogue One*.
Bovingdon Airfield near Hemel Hempstead served as the Yavin 4 Rebel Base in *Rogue One*.

Placename: Canary Wharf Underground Station, London, UK
Description: London's Canary Wharf Underground station was used as the Imperial security complex on Scarif in *Rogue One*.
Pymmes Park in London provided greenery for some Yavin 4 base scenes in *Rogue One*.
Iceland's Reynisfjara black sand beach portrayed the storm-swept planet Lah'mu in *Rogue One*.
